WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Support us and become VIP member 
to remove all ads from www.OpenSubtitles.org

2
00:00:30.407 --> 00:00:32.033
[chittering]

3
00:00:50.552 --> 00:00:52.554
[clicking. chittering]

4
00:00:56.725 --> 00:00:58.727
[low growling]

5
00:01:04.940 --> 00:01:07.986
[Mitsuki] Laser Array
Frequency Test 19-B.

6
00:01:08.820 --> 00:01:09.821
commence.

7
00:01:19.873 --> 00:01:20.957
Check levels.

8
00:01:22.167 --> 00:01:23.168
Levels are a go.

9
00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:25.962
Okay. We're operational.

10
00:01:27.714 --> 00:01:29.257
- I'm on my way out.
- Copy that.

11
00:01:30.383 --> 00:01:32.177
[alien clicking. chittering]

12
00:01:36.848 --> 00:01:39.267
[chittering grows
louder. distorted]

13
00:01:52.113 --> 00:01:54.658
[analyst] Yamato? Coming?

14
00:01:59.037 --> 00:02:00.205
On my way.

15
00:02:20.350 --> 00:02:21.935
[beeping]

16
00:02:33.488 --> 00:02:35.490
Go to 44 kilohertz.

17
00:02:37.784 --> 00:02:39.786
- Mm-mmm.
- [Mitsuki] Go to UHF.

18
00:02:41.246 --> 00:02:42.289
[analyst] No change.

19
00:02:42.789 --> 00:02:44.332
[colleague] We can
adjust amplitude.

20
00:02:44.833 --> 00:02:46.084
Why is it not working?

21
00:02:50.255 --> 00:02:51.256
Damn.

22
00:02:51.756 --> 00:02:54.217
Lost my bet. I thought
soonest would be tomorrow.

23
00:02:57.679 --> 00:02:58.680
What is this?

24
00:02:59.764 --> 00:03:02.142
Once in a while. the
alien emits this signal.

25
00:03:02.893 --> 00:03:05.270
We don't know why but
it is always the same.

26
00:03:05.854 --> 00:03:07.689
Here. Check it out.

27
00:03:09.316 --> 00:03:11.359
[both] And now.

28
00:03:13.111 --> 00:03:14.112
[analyst] That's it.

29
00:03:16.114 --> 00:03:17.115
[typing]

30
00:03:18.158 --> 00:03:19.284
What's it doing?

31
00:03:19.993 --> 00:03:21.369
[analyst] No idea.

32
00:03:21.995 --> 00:03:22.996
Transmit to Nikhil.

33
00:03:23.496 --> 00:03:26.416
- [colleague] Done.
- [analyst] It's probably just dying gasps.

34
00:03:27.334 --> 00:03:30.378
The ship is like a giant
damaged bio-organism.

35
00:03:30.462 --> 00:03:31.838
[colleague chuckles] Alien gas.

36
00:03:31.922 --> 00:03:34.507
[analyst chuckles] Hmm.

37
00:03:37.385 --> 00:03:38.678
How often does it happen?

38
00:03:39.346 --> 00:03:42.515
Sometimes it's days.
sometimes hours.

39
00:03:43.016 --> 00:03:44.684
Nikhil was all excited
in the beginning.

40
00:03:44.768 --> 00:03:46.978
but now it just goes
in the data slush pile.

41
00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:49.440
There's only so much
bandwidth in the apocalypse.

42
00:03:49.522 --> 00:03:51.282
[employee on comms] Base
Camp Three. come in.

43
00:03:52.150 --> 00:03:53.276
Base Camp Three here.

44
00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:55.403
Requesting Mitsuki
Yamato to the clinic.

45
00:03:56.029 --> 00:03:57.113
[colleague] Copy. Out.

46
00:03:57.822 --> 00:04:00.033
[analyst] Time to get your
brain scanned. [sighs]

47
00:04:00.533 --> 00:04:03.703
This is not necessary. I'm
fine. I need to get back.

48
00:04:03.787 --> 00:04:07.666
There's increased activity in
the angular gyrus and Wernicke's.

49
00:04:08.583 --> 00:04:12.170
Sounds or voices with
no identifiable source?

50
00:04:16.007 --> 00:04:18.677
I didn't say anything
yet. Why are you writing?

51
00:04:18.759 --> 00:04:21.159
And if you say you'll answer my
question when this is done...

52
00:04:21.221 --> 00:04:23.807
Then I'll answer your
question when this is done.

53
00:04:23.890 --> 00:04:26.059
I'm fine. I'll tell
you when I'm not.

54
00:04:26.142 --> 00:04:28.979
Actually. I'll tell
you when you're not.

55
00:04:31.314 --> 00:04:32.941
But I'll let you get back to it.

56
00:04:37.779 --> 00:04:39.531
How's it coming?

57
00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:41.241
The work.

58
00:04:42.325 --> 00:04:44.869
Any progress establishing
communication?

59
00:04:47.455 --> 00:04:48.540
Not really.

60
00:04:51.167 --> 00:04:52.168
But I can...

61
00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:57.090
Sometimes I feel like…

62
00:05:00.635 --> 00:05:04.264
Like I can feel it watching me.

63
00:05:05.056 --> 00:05:06.808
Be careful in there. okay?

64
00:05:07.684 --> 00:05:09.404
You don't want it prying
around in your head

65
00:05:09.436 --> 00:05:12.022
any more than it wants
you exposing its secrets.

66
00:05:14.566 --> 00:05:16.318
[people chattering]

67
00:05:30.957 --> 00:05:31.958
Mitsuki?

68
00:05:32.542 --> 00:05:33.543
I know him.

69
00:05:36.004 --> 00:05:37.005
[Maya] Oleg Varga.

70
00:05:37.797 --> 00:05:40.091
Won the Nobel Prize in
physics three years ago.

71
00:05:41.551 --> 00:05:42.552
Are you okay?

72
00:05:43.094 --> 00:05:44.554
- Yes. I'm...
- Fine.

73
00:05:45.305 --> 00:05:46.306
You know.

74
00:05:46.806 --> 00:05:48.767
now would be the time
to ask me questions.

75
00:05:49.267 --> 00:05:51.228
I think they need
you more than I do.

76
00:06:25.887 --> 00:06:26.888
What did you do?

77
00:06:27.639 --> 00:06:30.225
Nothing. We're running the
sequences. Still no response.

78
00:06:30.308 --> 00:06:31.476
Do that last one again.

79
00:06:32.477 --> 00:06:33.603
What?

80
00:06:33.687 --> 00:06:34.688
Do it again.

81
00:06:41.653 --> 00:06:43.113
[analyst on comms] Run 92. Go.

82
00:06:43.196 --> 00:06:44.197
[typing]

83
00:06:45.699 --> 00:06:46.741
Reading's stable.

84
00:06:47.742 --> 00:06:48.910
What's she doing?

85
00:06:48.994 --> 00:06:49.995
I don't know.

86
00:06:50.078 --> 00:06:51.413
Go back one more.

87
00:06:52.372 --> 00:06:53.582
[analyst] Run 91. go.

88
00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:56.585
Stable.

89
00:06:58.086 --> 00:06:59.504
Run 90. go.

90
00:06:59.588 --> 00:07:00.630
[typing]

91
00:07:01.256 --> 00:07:02.591
That one. Do it again.

92
00:07:03.091 --> 00:07:04.384
[colleague] Uh. Hey. Yamato.

93
00:07:05.093 --> 00:07:07.012
- W-What's going on?
- [Mitsuki] Come down here.

94
00:07:07.596 --> 00:07:08.597
Bring the transmitter.

95
00:07:13.476 --> 00:07:16.396
- [colleague] Think we got another burnout?
- [analyst] Yeah. We'll see.

96
00:07:20.108 --> 00:07:22.068
[colleague] These
things creep me out.

97
00:07:27.282 --> 00:07:30.243
[analyst] Yamato.
what's going on?

98
00:07:31.036 --> 00:07:32.078
Run it again.

99
00:07:34.706 --> 00:07:35.707
Run 90.

100
00:07:36.499 --> 00:07:37.500
[transmitter beeping]

101
00:07:37.584 --> 00:07:38.585
Go.

102
00:07:51.890 --> 00:07:52.891
Holy shi...

103
00:09:17.017 --> 00:09:18.476
[people chattering]

104
00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:38.747
[Luke] Why would you mark
a stolen car like that?

105
00:09:39.998 --> 00:09:40.999
What if they see?

106
00:09:41.917 --> 00:09:44.502
They care more about people
finding us than hiding.

107
00:09:45.253 --> 00:09:48.965
The Movement's number one directive
is we don't abandon people.

108
00:09:51.051 --> 00:09:52.052
It's a good rule.

109
00:09:56.223 --> 00:09:57.599
Where are you guys from?

110
00:09:58.975 --> 00:10:00.310
Marion. Ohio.

111
00:10:01.561 --> 00:10:07.484
It's this little nothing town.
kind of in the middle of nowhere.

112
00:10:08.318 --> 00:10:10.612
But I guess everywhere
is kind of nowhere now.

113
00:10:11.446 --> 00:10:12.656
What about you?

114
00:10:12.739 --> 00:10:13.907
New York.

115
00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:19.204
What was that language that you and
your mom were speaking this morning?

116
00:10:19.871 --> 00:10:21.206
She's teaching us Farsi.

117
00:10:22.249 --> 00:10:24.459
She grew up in Syria
but her mom's Iranian.

118
00:10:25.794 --> 00:10:29.005
I don't know. I guess she
misses home or something.

119
00:10:29.089 --> 00:10:31.633
[Clark] Ry. honey. Let's
get everybody loaded up.

120
00:10:32.425 --> 00:10:34.219
[thunder rumbling]

121
00:10:44.854 --> 00:10:46.894
I don't think your mother
would like you doing that.

122
00:11:00.954 --> 00:11:03.290
Hey. give me that can
before your mom sees.

123
00:11:03.373 --> 00:11:05.250
- [Aneesha] Sam.
- Ooh. Too late.

124
00:11:13.466 --> 00:11:14.509
Go inside.

125
00:11:15.093 --> 00:11:16.893
Make sure your sister's
things are all packed.

126
00:11:16.928 --> 00:11:18.096
I'll meet you there.

127
00:11:18.722 --> 00:11:21.099
There. In two minutes. Go.

128
00:11:30.817 --> 00:11:31.818
What is this?

129
00:11:34.613 --> 00:11:36.364
Just a kid being a kid. I guess.

130
00:11:39.117 --> 00:11:41.202
Take us to the next
refugee center.

131
00:11:43.246 --> 00:11:44.706
Do not talk to my kids.

132
00:11:46.166 --> 00:11:47.292
Okay.

133
00:11:51.046 --> 00:11:52.672
You ever let your guard down?

134
00:11:53.798 --> 00:11:55.133
What?

135
00:11:55.217 --> 00:11:57.344
I said. "Do you ever
let your guard down?"

136
00:11:59.763 --> 00:12:02.803
How do you expect your kids to do it if
you don't know how to do it yourself?

137
00:12:04.017 --> 00:12:06.478
Keeping this guard
up has kept us alive.

138
00:12:07.604 --> 00:12:09.648
We will take the
ride. thank you.

139
00:12:10.273 --> 00:12:11.733
We will be out of your way.

140
00:12:17.906 --> 00:12:19.157
[Clark] Okay. let's go!

141
00:12:24.204 --> 00:12:25.413
[tires screech]

142
00:12:27.207 --> 00:12:29.000
[phone ringing]

143
00:12:33.129 --> 00:12:34.256
Morning. Wade.

144
00:12:37.217 --> 00:12:39.553
- Morning. Rosey.
- Did you ask him yet?

145
00:12:39.636 --> 00:12:42.931
Rosey. he's busy. You know the military
has got the sheriff running around.

146
00:12:43.431 --> 00:12:47.102
- I'm pushing water uphill here. Wade.
- Hey. they brought a guy in last night.

147
00:12:47.185 --> 00:12:49.497
He's in the cell. Okay. transpo
will get him this afternoon.

148
00:12:49.521 --> 00:12:51.106
And what am I supposed
to do? Feed him?

149
00:12:51.189 --> 00:12:52.899
Yeah. I mean. that'd be humane.

150
00:12:53.525 --> 00:12:56.861
- Thirty-seven. as of yesterday. Wade.
- I know. Rosey. I know.

151
00:12:56.945 --> 00:12:58.363
I just don't know what I can...

152
00:12:59.406 --> 00:13:01.449
[sighs] I'll ask him.

153
00:13:02.325 --> 00:13:03.326
Please.

154
00:13:04.035 --> 00:13:05.537
- Thank you.
- [ringing continues]

155
00:13:07.622 --> 00:13:08.707
[sighs]

156
00:13:12.502 --> 00:13:14.754
It's about damn time!

157
00:13:14.838 --> 00:13:17.674
I've been here all night. Y'all
ain't got no on-duty officers?

158
00:13:17.757 --> 00:13:19.384
Now. come on. What's that about?

159
00:13:20.635 --> 00:13:24.806
Apologies. We're a little short-staffed
on account of the whole alien invasion.

160
00:13:26.057 --> 00:13:27.893
Transport will be here
in a couple of hours.

161
00:13:27.976 --> 00:13:29.686
Just sit tight until then.

162
00:13:31.813 --> 00:13:33.315
[ringing continues]

163
00:13:36.192 --> 00:13:38.069
Good morning. Miss Jilly.

164
00:13:39.487 --> 00:13:42.365
Okay. now. You know I'd call
if there was any news. right?

165
00:13:42.449 --> 00:13:43.950
I'm sorry. no.

166
00:13:45.201 --> 00:13:46.411
You holding up okay?

167
00:13:49.039 --> 00:13:51.166
I'm okay. ma'am.
Thanks for asking.

168
00:13:52.167 --> 00:13:54.252
Okay. I'll talk to you tomorrow.

169
00:13:55.879 --> 00:13:58.465
You guys got nothing to
hold me on. Check your logs.

170
00:13:59.174 --> 00:14:00.342
Go ahead. check them.

171
00:14:01.801 --> 00:14:04.346
You're talking to the wrong person.
buddy. I just answer phones.

172
00:14:04.429 --> 00:14:05.430
Okay. fine. Look.

173
00:14:07.891 --> 00:14:09.476
Please. I came in
here with a notebook.

174
00:14:09.559 --> 00:14:11.746
I just want to know where it
is and know that it's safe.

175
00:14:11.770 --> 00:14:13.772
I assure you your
belongings are safe.

176
00:14:13.855 --> 00:14:16.983
and will be returned to
you when the van gets here.

177
00:14:17.067 --> 00:14:19.402
I'll get you breakfast
in a bit. I've got work.

178
00:14:19.486 --> 00:14:22.030
Okay. like tracking down
all these missing people?

179
00:14:23.448 --> 00:14:26.493
I mean there's gotta be at least
30-something posters on these walls

180
00:14:26.576 --> 00:14:29.579
and it looks to me you're gonna
need all the help that you can get.

181
00:14:29.663 --> 00:14:31.957
How about you let me out this
cell and get me my notebook

182
00:14:32.040 --> 00:14:34.644
before you run out of citizens to
go missing and walls to put 'em on.

183
00:14:34.668 --> 00:14:37.295
Why? 'Cause you're gonna
help me find these people?

184
00:14:37.379 --> 00:14:38.964
If they give me
my notebook. yeah.

185
00:14:43.134 --> 00:14:44.386
You've lost someone.

186
00:14:47.097 --> 00:14:48.098
You got that look.

187
00:14:59.734 --> 00:15:01.736
Hmm. Which one's yours?

188
00:15:02.946 --> 00:15:04.406
Maybe I can help you find them.

189
00:15:05.824 --> 00:15:06.866
That's not funny.

190
00:15:06.950 --> 00:15:09.244
- I'm not trying to be funny.
- Okay.

191
00:15:11.413 --> 00:15:13.164
See. I get the savior complex.

192
00:15:14.291 --> 00:15:18.253
Hell. I wish some random guy
in a jail cell had the answer.

193
00:15:18.336 --> 00:15:21.715
but I'm afraid Mr...
Sorry. what's your name?

194
00:15:21.798 --> 00:15:23.174
Cole. Trevante Cole.

195
00:15:23.258 --> 00:15:26.177
Navy SEAL. Two tours
Afghanistan. one tour Iraq.

196
00:15:26.261 --> 00:15:27.262
One of them.

197
00:15:30.432 --> 00:15:31.808
Let me show you something.

198
00:15:37.105 --> 00:15:38.899
Mmm. This guy's my favorite.

199
00:15:40.025 --> 00:15:43.612
This man hiked all
the way from Alaska

200
00:15:43.695 --> 00:15:46.615
because he heard we had
an alien-fighting brigade

201
00:15:46.698 --> 00:15:48.033
and he wanted to join.

202
00:15:48.116 --> 00:15:49.284
[chuckles]

203
00:15:49.367 --> 00:15:51.536
This woman saw little
green men in a dream.

204
00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:53.455
wanted to make sure
we had a sketch.

205
00:15:53.955 --> 00:15:57.542
This lady talks to
the recently abducted.

206
00:15:57.626 --> 00:15:58.627
Can you do that?

207
00:15:59.586 --> 00:16:02.130
You know what every single one
of these people had in common?

208
00:16:02.214 --> 00:16:06.760
Every one of them came looking for an
answer. a reason. some bigger picture.

209
00:16:06.843 --> 00:16:10.305
But not one of them gave
a goddamn about this town.

210
00:16:11.723 --> 00:16:15.769
Jacquelyn ran the pet grooming
business in town for 20 years.

211
00:16:16.603 --> 00:16:21.775
Nels has three sons. seven grandkids.
and his wife still calls every morning

212
00:16:21.858 --> 00:16:24.194
to make sure that
there's no news.

213
00:16:24.277 --> 00:16:26.321
Eileen Grady there. we
went to school together.

214
00:16:26.404 --> 00:16:27.656
She was Deputy here.

215
00:16:27.739 --> 00:16:31.076
That's who I've lost.
Everyone on these walls.

216
00:16:31.159 --> 00:16:33.578
And all those people out there
trying to live their lives.

217
00:16:33.662 --> 00:16:35.014
that's who I'm
trying to keep safe.

218
00:16:35.038 --> 00:16:37.540
So you and your magic notebook

219
00:16:37.624 --> 00:16:40.669
can sit tight for a few hours
while I get back to work.

220
00:16:40.752 --> 00:16:42.712
And I'll make sure you
get on that transpo.

221
00:16:42.796 --> 00:16:46.007
I'll even throw in coffee
and a muffin if you hush up.

222
00:16:52.264 --> 00:16:54.015
We need to amplify the signal.

223
00:16:54.099 --> 00:16:55.475
[typing]

224
00:16:56.726 --> 00:16:57.811
Do you think it knows?

225
00:17:00.230 --> 00:17:02.023
That we triggered
its cloaking signal?

226
00:17:06.695 --> 00:17:07.696
No idea.

227
00:17:08.572 --> 00:17:09.698
[analyst] This is nuts.

228
00:17:10.282 --> 00:17:12.242
You've been here.
what? A few days?

229
00:17:12.993 --> 00:17:15.286
We've never gotten near
this kind of discovery.

230
00:17:15.786 --> 00:17:19.248
Okay. stay in this frequency
range. Run it through VHF.

231
00:17:27.757 --> 00:17:29.718
[alien clicking. chittering]

232
00:17:49.279 --> 00:17:51.406
- [colleague] Yamato.
- [analyst typing]

233
00:17:53.950 --> 00:17:54.993
Yamato.

234
00:17:58.622 --> 00:17:59.623
[analyst] You okay?

235
00:18:01.875 --> 00:18:02.876
Yeah.

236
00:18:04.502 --> 00:18:05.503
I'm fine.

237
00:18:08.048 --> 00:18:09.382
I need some air.

238
00:18:20.268 --> 00:18:22.103
[birds shrieking. squawking]

239
00:18:27.651 --> 00:18:29.277
[in Japanese] You won't win.

240
00:18:30.862 --> 00:18:33.156
We have one of your
ships down here.

241
00:18:48.588 --> 00:18:50.006
[in English] I know what it is!

242
00:18:50.799 --> 00:18:53.093
It's a distress call.
Pull up the history.

243
00:18:53.176 --> 00:18:54.678
- What?
- The signal.

244
00:18:55.262 --> 00:18:58.014
I need to see every single
instance of the past four months.

245
00:18:58.098 --> 00:19:01.059
- [analyst] It's not consistent. Look.
- [colleague] T-There is no pattern.

246
00:19:01.726 --> 00:19:02.727
[Mitsuki] Watch.

247
00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:04.646
[typing]

248
00:19:09.401 --> 00:19:11.069
It fits with a cubic spline.

249
00:19:11.152 --> 00:19:12.279
[analyst gasps]

250
00:19:12.362 --> 00:19:13.363
It's not a dying gasp.

251
00:19:14.531 --> 00:19:15.532
It's a Mayday.

252
00:19:16.199 --> 00:19:17.909
It's sending an SOS.

253
00:19:17.993 --> 00:19:19.202
Sending it where?

254
00:19:19.286 --> 00:19:20.996
Now where would you send an SOS

255
00:19:21.079 --> 00:19:23.373
if you were the one
downed ship on our planet?

256
00:19:26.418 --> 00:19:29.588
If I'm right. the next
signal is at 5:32.

257
00:19:30.630 --> 00:19:32.507
You wanna tell night
shift not to come in?

258
00:19:33.758 --> 00:19:35.444
You've already had four
hours on the inside.

259
00:19:35.468 --> 00:19:37.304
That exceeds your
proximity quota.

260
00:19:37.387 --> 00:19:39.806
You wanna tell me
not to come in?

261
00:19:41.224 --> 00:19:44.144
Okay. So. if we can predict
the next signal. then what?

262
00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:46.980
We stop it from sending?

263
00:19:47.063 --> 00:19:49.941
No. We hack it.

264
00:20:09.336 --> 00:20:11.254
[Maya] What are you
doing here so late?

265
00:20:12.339 --> 00:20:13.590
What's the time?

266
00:20:13.673 --> 00:20:17.219
Only about 11 hours after
your allotted shift?

267
00:20:30.398 --> 00:20:32.275
I'm on the verge
of something here.

268
00:20:33.068 --> 00:20:34.069
[chuckles] Yes.

269
00:20:36.029 --> 00:20:37.030
Yes. you are.

270
00:20:40.158 --> 00:20:41.326
You didn't ask the question

271
00:20:41.409 --> 00:20:43.954
because you don't want to
contemplate the answer.

272
00:20:46.456 --> 00:20:49.209
Every scientist in that room
had one thing in common.

273
00:20:51.628 --> 00:20:53.129
They all said they were fine.

274
00:20:54.965 --> 00:20:57.133
and they weren't fine.

275
00:21:00.178 --> 00:21:02.806
They all wanted to stare
into the mind of that alien…

276
00:21:05.141 --> 00:21:06.685
until they lost their own.

277
00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:12.607
I know you think
you're different.

278
00:21:14.943 --> 00:21:16.278
But so did they.

279
00:21:18.738 --> 00:21:20.490
Every single one of them.

280
00:21:21.575 --> 00:21:22.617
Yes.

281
00:21:23.785 --> 00:21:25.996
"Yes" was the answer
to your question.

282
00:21:29.499 --> 00:21:30.500
[inhales sharply]

283
00:21:33.128 --> 00:21:37.215
I believed Hinata
was on that ship.

284
00:21:41.636 --> 00:21:43.221
And I blame myself…

285
00:21:45.348 --> 00:21:46.766
for what happened to her.

286
00:21:49.936 --> 00:21:50.937
To the world.

287
00:21:53.315 --> 00:21:54.316
I know.

288
00:21:57.694 --> 00:22:00.822
But do you think it will make it
better if you punish yourself?

289
00:22:06.077 --> 00:22:10.874
It might make it better
if I punish them.

290
00:22:12.167 --> 00:22:13.877
[alarm beeping]

291
00:22:14.669 --> 00:22:15.879
[clears throat]

292
00:22:15.962 --> 00:22:17.130
It's time.

293
00:22:18.048 --> 00:22:19.049
Follow me.

294
00:22:23.887 --> 00:22:25.096
All systems running.

295
00:22:27.349 --> 00:22:28.892
- [colleague] Hi. Maya.
- Hey. Misha.

296
00:22:29.601 --> 00:22:31.102
[beeping]

297
00:22:33.104 --> 00:22:37.192
Three. two. one.

298
00:22:37.859 --> 00:22:41.738
Yes! Yes. we got you! We
got you. you little bastard!

299
00:22:41.821 --> 00:22:43.448
What just happened?

300
00:22:43.531 --> 00:22:46.826
We... She just figured out
how to hack the mother ship.

301
00:22:49.871 --> 00:22:54.501
And you think this SOS signal
is going up to the mother ship?

302
00:22:55.210 --> 00:22:56.211
[Mitsuki] Yes.

303
00:22:57.295 --> 00:22:59.089
It must not be receiving.

304
00:22:59.172 --> 00:23:02.175
Nothing's come down to retrieve
the ship or the… [chuckles] …alien.

305
00:23:02.259 --> 00:23:03.419
[Mitsuki] We don't know that.

306
00:23:03.468 --> 00:23:07.722
Well. I think I'd have noticed an
alien SWAT team on my doorstep.

307
00:23:08.223 --> 00:23:10.976
Maybe it's receiving but
decided one downed ship

308
00:23:11.059 --> 00:23:12.769
isn't enough for
a rescue mission.

309
00:23:18.316 --> 00:23:19.651
This is insane.

310
00:23:20.193 --> 00:23:22.612
Which is why she thought
you would appreciate it.

311
00:23:25.115 --> 00:23:26.866
Maya. what's your
role in all this?

312
00:23:26.950 --> 00:23:29.077
- Oh. I'm just here for moral support.
- [Nikhil] Oh!

313
00:23:29.160 --> 00:23:30.870
Some people find
you intimidating.

314
00:23:31.746 --> 00:23:33.623
Thank you. Thank
you for that. Maya.

315
00:23:35.709 --> 00:23:37.627
- Not her.
- No.

316
00:23:38.920 --> 00:23:44.467
So you're proposing that we piggyback
on this "maybe" transmission.

317
00:23:44.551 --> 00:23:45.677
And... and what?

318
00:23:46.261 --> 00:23:48.263
- Hack into their mother ship?
- Yes.

319
00:23:48.346 --> 00:23:51.516
[giggles] You're right. I
love how insane this is.

320
00:23:54.102 --> 00:23:55.770
But what's the endgame?

321
00:23:57.814 --> 00:24:01.568
Let's... Let's say your... Your
premise proves right and we can…

322
00:24:03.612 --> 00:24:04.779
see the matrix.

323
00:24:05.530 --> 00:24:06.531
Then what. Neo?

324
00:24:07.741 --> 00:24:11.369
The aliens. they are
getting to Earth somehow.

325
00:24:12.329 --> 00:24:15.457
We don't know why there's more
here every day. everywhere.

326
00:24:16.082 --> 00:24:19.169
And it's because they've been
using this cloaking technology.

327
00:24:20.128 --> 00:24:24.007
If we can get a look at
them. we can target them.

328
00:24:25.342 --> 00:24:27.636
You want to decloak
their transport ships?

329
00:24:27.719 --> 00:24:29.554
And shoot them out of the sky.

330
00:24:30.722 --> 00:24:31.806
There's a downside.

331
00:24:32.432 --> 00:24:33.934
What could possibly
be a downside?

332
00:24:34.017 --> 00:24:35.936
[Maya] Anything we
hit crashes to Earth.

333
00:24:36.019 --> 00:24:38.813
That carrier out there is
the size of a small city.

334
00:24:38.897 --> 00:24:41.024
We risk killing more
of us than them.

335
00:24:45.779 --> 00:24:46.905
Stalingrad.

336
00:24:49.407 --> 00:24:51.117
The Battle of Stalingrad.

337
00:24:51.701 --> 00:24:54.788
Everyone thought it was the
nukes on Japan. apologies.

338
00:24:54.871 --> 00:24:57.749
or D-Day that turned the
tide against the Nazis.

339
00:24:57.832 --> 00:25:02.128
but it was the win in Stalingrad
that Germany never recovered from.

340
00:25:02.879 --> 00:25:04.506
The deadliest battle
in World War II.

341
00:25:04.589 --> 00:25:08.593
The Soviets lost over
a million people.

342
00:25:09.719 --> 00:25:11.012
but they pushed them back.

343
00:25:12.722 --> 00:25:14.558
This is our Stalingrad.

344
00:25:16.309 --> 00:25:17.394
[exhales]

345
00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:21.773
Besides. Earth's
surface is 71% water.

346
00:25:22.816 --> 00:25:23.942
I'll take our odds.

347
00:25:25.443 --> 00:25:27.946
- Are you insane?
- [laughs]

348
00:25:28.029 --> 00:25:30.031
Uh. Maya... Dr. Castillo.

349
00:25:30.115 --> 00:25:32.659
Do you wanna answer that question
from a clinical perspective?

350
00:25:32.742 --> 00:25:35.287
And does anyone ever say
yes to that question?

351
00:25:36.496 --> 00:25:38.790
You wanted a win? I'm
offering you a chance to...

352
00:25:38.873 --> 00:25:42.627
To order all of my nuclear
arms operatives to. quote.

353
00:25:42.711 --> 00:25:46.256
"Look up at the sky at 0942
UTC and be at DEFCON 1."

354
00:25:46.756 --> 00:25:48.174
That's correct. ma'am.

355
00:25:48.258 --> 00:25:51.219
And if they see anything. a
particularly vague concept.

356
00:25:51.303 --> 00:25:52.512
to shoot it down.

357
00:25:52.596 --> 00:25:53.805
Right.

358
00:25:53.889 --> 00:25:55.932
We'll need the speed and
range of tactical nukes.

359
00:25:57.225 --> 00:26:01.062
We have something. Benya.
We really have something.

360
00:26:02.022 --> 00:26:04.357
I don't like to be wrong.
so you know I wouldn't ask

361
00:26:04.441 --> 00:26:06.985
if I didn't think there
was a very good chance.

362
00:26:07.068 --> 00:26:08.194
"A very good chance."

363
00:26:09.613 --> 00:26:10.614
How long?

364
00:26:12.073 --> 00:26:14.159
- Madam?
- How long would you like

365
00:26:14.242 --> 00:26:18.121
my nuclear operatives to stare at the sky
in the hope that something shall appear?

366
00:26:21.833 --> 00:26:23.084
I need an answer.

367
00:26:23.168 --> 00:26:24.211
I don't know.

368
00:26:24.294 --> 00:26:25.629
[whispers] Then guess.

369
00:26:27.214 --> 00:26:28.298
Thirty minutes.

370
00:26:31.509 --> 00:26:33.011
Thirty minutes. Madam President.

371
00:26:34.304 --> 00:26:35.347
Thirty minutes.

372
00:26:35.847 --> 00:26:38.767
And tell them. targeting
needs to be ready to lock on.

373
00:26:39.267 --> 00:26:41.645
I don't know how long we'll
have before they cut the signal.

374
00:26:42.437 --> 00:26:44.564
Is there anything else I
can do for you. Miss Yamato?

375
00:26:44.648 --> 00:26:45.690
[chuckles]

376
00:26:46.274 --> 00:26:47.734
No. that's all.

377
00:26:48.401 --> 00:26:49.736
Thank you. Madam President.

378
00:26:50.779 --> 00:26:51.780
Ta-ta.

379
00:27:03.166 --> 00:27:04.376
[Rose] Morning. Sheriff.

380
00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:08.129
Morning. Rose.

381
00:27:08.213 --> 00:27:09.214
You got a minute?

382
00:27:09.881 --> 00:27:11.943
If we got another problem
with this coffee machine...

383
00:27:11.967 --> 00:27:15.345
Oh. no. no. no. Well…
[chuckles] …actually we do.

384
00:27:15.428 --> 00:27:17.180
But that's not what
I wanted to discuss.

385
00:27:18.348 --> 00:27:19.349
I was just...

386
00:27:20.058 --> 00:27:23.645
Well. I was wondering if you'd taken
a look at those three new cases.

387
00:27:23.728 --> 00:27:25.855
I was looking at where
they were last seen.

388
00:27:25.939 --> 00:27:27.732
and maybe there are
some kind of clues.

389
00:27:27.816 --> 00:27:30.986
Rose. We're trying
our best. I promise.

390
00:27:31.069 --> 00:27:32.153
We're stretched thin.

391
00:27:32.237 --> 00:27:35.448
I know. I know. Which is
why I compiled everything.

392
00:27:35.532 --> 00:27:38.535
Put it all down along with any
connection to the other cases.

393
00:27:39.035 --> 00:27:41.788
Rosey. leave it to
the professionals.

394
00:27:42.372 --> 00:27:45.750
Right. Well. just like you said.

395
00:27:45.834 --> 00:27:49.296
With everyone being stretched
thin and more folks disappearing.

396
00:27:49.379 --> 00:27:50.422
feels like every day now.

397
00:27:50.505 --> 00:27:52.425
I thought you'd appreciate
an extra set of hands.

398
00:27:52.465 --> 00:27:53.633
I do. I really do.

399
00:27:53.717 --> 00:27:54.885
Thank you. Rosey.

400
00:27:57.137 --> 00:27:59.848
Now let's get that coffee
machine working again. shall we?

401
00:28:04.019 --> 00:28:05.103
[scoffs]

402
00:28:08.148 --> 00:28:09.274
[huffs]

403
00:28:09.357 --> 00:28:11.151
Damn it. [inhales]

404
00:28:12.277 --> 00:28:14.362
- [Rose sighs]
- [Trevante] You all right?

405
00:28:14.446 --> 00:28:16.740
[Rose huffs] Left my job at
the shop to make a difference

406
00:28:16.823 --> 00:28:19.159
and the only thing
I'm making is coffee.

407
00:28:20.577 --> 00:28:21.703
Not even that.

408
00:28:21.786 --> 00:28:24.289
- Maybe. like I said. I can help.
- Yeah?

409
00:28:24.372 --> 00:28:26.708
Just like the military
said when they got here?

410
00:28:28.668 --> 00:28:30.587
"We can help. Just
follow protocol."

411
00:28:30.670 --> 00:28:32.589
Y'all love that
word. "protocol."

412
00:28:32.672 --> 00:28:33.715
And what they done?

413
00:28:33.798 --> 00:28:38.011
Just come in. took over. turned
the library into some kind of lab.

414
00:28:38.094 --> 00:28:41.306
Their big base over there?
Used to be our high school.

415
00:28:41.806 --> 00:28:44.935
Turned Ben Shelton's farm into
their supply depot or some shit.

416
00:28:45.018 --> 00:28:47.896
Ground zero in the
Americas. lucky us.

417
00:28:47.979 --> 00:28:50.774
Our people keep disappearing.
but no one cares.

418
00:28:50.857 --> 00:28:52.734
Because what's 37
missing people.

419
00:28:52.817 --> 00:28:55.362
when a quarter of the
world's gone dead or missing?

420
00:28:55.946 --> 00:28:57.948
But every single one
of them had a name.

421
00:28:58.531 --> 00:29:01.368
Everyone had a date
that they went missing.

422
00:29:01.451 --> 00:29:04.412
But soldiers treat those
dates like a death sentence

423
00:29:04.496 --> 00:29:05.914
to put on their tombstone.

424
00:29:05.997 --> 00:29:06.998
Dates.

425
00:29:15.882 --> 00:29:17.384
It's not a star.

426
00:29:19.261 --> 00:29:20.345
It's a badge.

427
00:29:21.346 --> 00:29:22.889
And those are the numbers.

428
00:29:24.641 --> 00:29:26.761
That was the sheriff right
there? That old guy. Tyson?

429
00:29:26.810 --> 00:29:29.229
Sure was. And let me tell you.
he would have done something

430
00:29:29.312 --> 00:29:30.313
if he was still here.

431
00:29:30.397 --> 00:29:31.690
[Trevante] What happened to him?

432
00:29:32.190 --> 00:29:33.900
[Rose] One of the
first to go missing.

433
00:29:33.984 --> 00:29:36.987
Night of his retirement
party. How's that for a joke?

434
00:29:38.863 --> 00:29:40.198
He brought me here.

435
00:29:40.282 --> 00:29:42.367
- That's not the kind of joke I meant.
- I'm serious.

436
00:29:42.450 --> 00:29:44.703
Hey. look. I need you
to get me that notebook.

437
00:29:44.786 --> 00:29:48.140
- We've been over this. It's in lockup. I...
- Look at me. Look at me. Look at me. okay?

438
00:29:48.164 --> 00:29:49.444
I know you've heard this before.

439
00:29:49.499 --> 00:29:52.752
and I know I sound as crazy as the rest.
but I'm telling you I've lost everything.

440
00:29:53.253 --> 00:29:56.006
Everything. I've lost hope down to
this second. but I'm telling you.

441
00:29:56.089 --> 00:29:57.149
You think you're desperate?

442
00:29:57.173 --> 00:30:00.218
Try sitting months in an Internet
hub trading rations for minutes.

443
00:30:00.302 --> 00:30:02.697
and staying there till 4:00 in
the morning every single night.

444
00:30:02.721 --> 00:30:05.974
Getting dead end. after dead end.
after dead end. getting nothing.

445
00:30:06.474 --> 00:30:10.103
Until now. Right this second.
I've found something. Rose.

446
00:30:10.186 --> 00:30:13.773
I need you to get me that
notebook. okay? So I can show you.

447
00:30:13.857 --> 00:30:17.110
And maybe. just maybe.
we can help each other.

448
00:30:19.613 --> 00:30:22.908
And you can save your town. and I
can win a goddamn war for a change.

449
00:30:24.868 --> 00:30:27.621
Look. Rose. You need me
like I need you. okay?

450
00:30:30.165 --> 00:30:33.835
Four months ago. a couple of strangers.
you know. they asked me for help.

451
00:30:34.920 --> 00:30:36.046
Kids.

452
00:30:36.129 --> 00:30:38.006
And I didn't wanna
help them. I didn't.

453
00:30:39.216 --> 00:30:40.936
But I didn't have
anything else left to lose

454
00:30:40.967 --> 00:30:43.970
and that was the first time I actually
felt like I'd made a difference.

455
00:30:45.222 --> 00:30:47.891
So. now I'm asking you from
the bottom of my heart.

456
00:30:49.768 --> 00:30:51.019
what do you have to lose?

457
00:31:01.529 --> 00:31:03.657
- [static on radio]
- [person on radio] Help! Help!

458
00:31:03.740 --> 00:31:05.492
- Ryder.
- Help us! Anybody?

459
00:31:05.575 --> 00:31:07.535
Mayday? What is your
status and location?

460
00:31:07.619 --> 00:31:09.788
I repeat. what is your
status and location?

461
00:31:09.871 --> 00:31:11.414
Uh. we're trapped in the ravine!

462
00:31:11.498 --> 00:31:14.501
Give me your location. Please.
just specify your location.

463
00:31:14.584 --> 00:31:17.212
- I don't know. Elk's Pass.
- Elk's Pass.

464
00:31:18.255 --> 00:31:20.215
Hey there. folks. We may
have a rescue situation.

465
00:31:20.298 --> 00:31:21.299
What are you doing?

466
00:31:21.383 --> 00:31:23.343
[Ryder] Got it. Next
turn's onto Highway 6.

467
00:31:23.426 --> 00:31:25.178
Hanley. Jackson.
Chrissy. with me.

468
00:31:25.679 --> 00:31:27.556
- [Hanley] Copy that.
- [Chrissy] Copy that.

469
00:31:30.392 --> 00:31:32.185
You said you would
get us to safety.

470
00:31:32.269 --> 00:31:35.021
And I will. as soon as we
check out this distress call.

471
00:31:35.105 --> 00:31:36.541
- Let us out.
- In the middle of nowhere?

472
00:31:36.565 --> 00:31:38.834
- Just let us out. Let us out right here!
- [Clark] Listen...

473
00:31:38.858 --> 00:31:41.736
- [Aneesha] Stop the car.
- I am gonna get you to safety.

474
00:31:41.820 --> 00:31:44.489
- We just gotta do this first.
- [Aneesha] Why?

475
00:31:44.573 --> 00:31:48.326
I told you. We help people.
okay? It's what we do.

476
00:31:58.712 --> 00:32:00.922
Notify me when
submarines are in place.

477
00:32:01.006 --> 00:32:02.007
India's holding.

478
00:32:03.091 --> 00:32:04.092
[Benya clears throat]

479
00:32:07.429 --> 00:32:08.430
General.

480
00:32:08.513 --> 00:32:09.514
Madam President.

481
00:32:09.598 --> 00:32:12.267
this directive to bypass the
chain of command is troubling.

482
00:32:12.350 --> 00:32:13.351
to say the least.

483
00:32:13.435 --> 00:32:17.314
Necessary. We have to trust our operators.
We may only have a brief window.

484
00:32:17.397 --> 00:32:21.234
I trust my operators.
It's yours I distrust.

485
00:32:22.027 --> 00:32:24.195
I don't relish ICBMs
dropping on my head

486
00:32:24.279 --> 00:32:26.865
because some 20-year-old
lacked restraint.

487
00:32:30.368 --> 00:32:33.580
Tell all operators. if they
miss. to detonate in the air.

488
00:32:34.247 --> 00:32:36.082
Let's try not to
shoot each other.

489
00:32:38.835 --> 00:32:41.087
- Happy?
- Not particularly.

490
00:32:41.671 --> 00:32:42.672
Well. who is?

491
00:32:45.800 --> 00:32:48.220
[Clark] Hanley? Jackson?
Chrissy? Here we go.

492
00:32:49.596 --> 00:32:50.597
[Hanley] Copy that.

493
00:32:51.181 --> 00:32:52.182
[Chrissy] Copy that.

494
00:33:04.402 --> 00:33:06.404
You know? For my 30th birthday.

495
00:33:06.488 --> 00:33:08.782
I had the biggest firework
display in history.

496
00:33:08.865 --> 00:33:10.951
Thirty barges. [chuckles]

497
00:33:11.034 --> 00:33:12.953
They said you could
see it from space.

498
00:33:15.247 --> 00:33:16.373
Trended for a week.

499
00:33:18.750 --> 00:33:21.670
Do you still want my clinical
evaluation of your sanity?

500
00:33:35.141 --> 00:33:36.142
You okay?

501
00:33:39.396 --> 00:33:41.064
The last time we fired at them…

502
00:33:45.652 --> 00:33:47.696
was the last time
I heard her voice.

503
00:33:52.534 --> 00:33:53.702
This time's different.

504
00:33:59.332 --> 00:34:00.333
Hmm.

505
00:34:03.378 --> 00:34:05.046
I think you can bury someone…

506
00:34:08.465 --> 00:34:09.467
a memory…

507
00:34:11.469 --> 00:34:12.470
a feeling.

508
00:34:16.349 --> 00:34:18.518
But one moment can
bring it all back.

509
00:34:23.273 --> 00:34:25.733
[inhales] What part
of my brain is that?

510
00:34:28.903 --> 00:34:30.030
The human part.

511
00:34:35.076 --> 00:34:38.038
[Wade] Military wants us on the
streets at dawn looking up at the sky.

512
00:34:38.121 --> 00:34:39.664
Some kinda action
they got going on.

513
00:34:39.748 --> 00:34:41.749
Okay. Davids. Garcia. saddle up.

514
00:34:42.374 --> 00:34:44.102
- You're riding with me. Wade.
- [Wade] Sheriff.

515
00:34:44.126 --> 00:34:45.878
[sheriff] Come on.
Let's go. Carmichael.

516
00:34:46.378 --> 00:34:48.757
- What's going on?
- Oh. Hey. Rosey.

517
00:34:48.840 --> 00:34:51.300
Transport's being held till
whatever they got going on's done.

518
00:34:51.384 --> 00:34:53.178
Think you can watch him
a couple more hours?

519
00:34:53.260 --> 00:34:56.765
Yeah. I'ma stay here. Get
that coffee machine working.

520
00:34:56.847 --> 00:34:58.808
- You're a savior. Rosey.
- [Rose chuckles]

521
00:34:58.892 --> 00:34:59.893
A savior.

522
00:35:11.821 --> 00:35:13.573
All right. open it up.

523
00:35:16.534 --> 00:35:18.554
- You did this?
- No. the kid. The kid that I helped.

524
00:35:18.578 --> 00:35:22.374
He drew it. I mean. he would see
things. See what the aliens would see.

525
00:35:22.874 --> 00:35:24.417
They like comic books like us?

526
00:35:24.501 --> 00:35:26.753
Go a few pages
back. Three or four.

527
00:35:28.463 --> 00:35:31.007
There. He drew that
over four months ago.

528
00:35:31.591 --> 00:35:33.260
And at first. I
thought it was a star.

529
00:35:33.343 --> 00:35:36.304
Like a planet or something.
but don't you recognize it?

530
00:35:37.138 --> 00:35:40.016
That's the same shape as
Sheriff Tyson's badge.

531
00:35:42.686 --> 00:35:44.020
Am I wrong?

532
00:35:44.104 --> 00:35:45.105
[scoffs]

533
00:35:46.982 --> 00:35:48.817
Could just be a coincidence.

534
00:35:48.900 --> 00:35:51.570
Go get his flyer. please.

535
00:35:57.534 --> 00:36:00.414
Now check the numbers in the book and
check the date that he was missing.

536
00:36:10.255 --> 00:36:13.049
See? The answers are in there.

537
00:36:14.885 --> 00:36:16.245
They brought me
here for a reason.

538
00:36:25.520 --> 00:36:28.148
The answers are here.

539
00:36:30.984 --> 00:36:33.862
[Hanley panting] We got a
family of three stuck in a car.

540
00:36:34.988 --> 00:36:36.406
I counted six aliens.

541
00:36:36.990 --> 00:36:38.491
They're coming from all sides.

542
00:36:43.330 --> 00:36:45.457
[Clark] Suit up.
All the throwers.

543
00:36:47.959 --> 00:36:49.628
[people chattering]

544
00:36:52.422 --> 00:36:53.548
Got a family trapped.

545
00:36:54.549 --> 00:36:56.468
Half a dozen aliens
pinning them down.

546
00:36:59.137 --> 00:37:00.615
- Ry. you're staying.
- I'm going with you.

547
00:37:00.639 --> 00:37:02.519
- Not this time. Ry!
- No. Dad. I always come...

548
00:37:10.440 --> 00:37:12.418
You're a safe distance.
Nothing's gonna happen to you.

549
00:37:12.442 --> 00:37:13.902
Safe distance?

550
00:37:13.985 --> 00:37:15.528
I gave you my word.
I keep my word.

551
00:37:18.823 --> 00:37:20.200
But if things go sideways…

552
00:37:25.956 --> 00:37:26.957
drive away.

553
00:37:33.338 --> 00:37:34.339
[static on radio]

554
00:37:41.680 --> 00:37:44.408
- [Clark] Quick and quiet.
- [Hanley] Copy. Jackson. you're on assist.

555
00:37:44.432 --> 00:37:46.726
- [Jackson] Copy that.
- [Clark] On my signal.

556
00:37:48.061 --> 00:37:49.062
Go. go. go.

557
00:37:51.898 --> 00:37:53.942
[shouting in distance]

558
00:37:54.025 --> 00:37:56.778
[Clark] Go. go. go. Guys.
ready? [continues. indistinct]

559
00:37:56.861 --> 00:37:58.488
Go. go!

560
00:37:58.572 --> 00:38:00.073
[person screaming]

561
00:38:03.034 --> 00:38:07.163
The message will broadcast continuously
on all emergency signals for 30 minutes.

562
00:38:07.664 --> 00:38:09.541
or until you give
the order to stop.

563
00:38:18.675 --> 00:38:20.886
My fellow global citizens.

564
00:38:22.345 --> 00:38:24.598
Today at 0942 UTC.

565
00:38:25.599 --> 00:38:28.768
the global community will
attempt a coordinated response

566
00:38:29.686 --> 00:38:32.772
to the alien aggressors
who have invaded our world.

567
00:38:33.940 --> 00:38:39.821
For months now. we've been
outnumbered. outflanked. outgunned.

568
00:38:41.114 --> 00:38:43.283
I cannot guarantee
that we will succeed.

569
00:38:43.909 --> 00:38:45.160
Load sequence.

570
00:38:45.243 --> 00:38:47.412
- But what I can say…
- [analyst] Loading.

571
00:38:47.495 --> 00:38:50.081
…is we'll try hit them
back where it hurts.

572
00:38:51.875 --> 00:38:54.085
Let them feel a fraction
of what we feel.

573
00:38:54.586 --> 00:38:55.837
[Hanley] One more incoming.

574
00:38:56.379 --> 00:38:57.422
[Clark] Jackson. cover me.

575
00:38:57.923 --> 00:39:00.759
Chrissy. Chrissy. You got eyes
on it? Left! To your left!

576
00:39:01.343 --> 00:39:03.511
[Benya] My father used to say.

577
00:39:03.595 --> 00:39:06.806
"Never let them see you
with your head bowed."

578
00:39:09.809 --> 00:39:13.104
So I ask you now. to look up.

579
00:39:17.317 --> 00:39:19.569
- Five. four…
- Look up.

580
00:39:19.653 --> 00:39:20.922
- Let us no longer fear…
- Three.

581
00:39:20.946 --> 00:39:23.240
- …the stars and the sky above.
- Two.

582
00:39:23.323 --> 00:39:24.449
One.

583
00:39:24.950 --> 00:39:25.951
Go.

584
00:39:26.034 --> 00:39:27.327
[typing]

585
00:39:28.119 --> 00:39:29.162
[analyst] Onboarded.

586
00:39:29.746 --> 00:39:31.790
Hold. Hold.

587
00:39:36.836 --> 00:39:37.837
Halt.

588
00:39:38.922 --> 00:39:39.923
Now what?

589
00:39:42.968 --> 00:39:43.969
We wait.

590
00:39:52.352 --> 00:39:53.353
[Chrissy] Clark!

591
00:39:53.436 --> 00:39:56.565
- Behind you! Behind you!
- [Clark groans. screams]

592
00:39:56.648 --> 00:39:58.608
- [Chrissy] Clark!
- Ryder! Ryder!

593
00:39:58.692 --> 00:40:00.527
[Clark] Let's go. let's go!

594
00:40:00.610 --> 00:40:03.113
- Mom!
- [Aneesha] Ryder. come back!

595
00:40:04.781 --> 00:40:08.243
[Clark] Hold steady!
Zeb's down! Zeb's down!

596
00:40:09.369 --> 00:40:13.790
Mom. please! We have to help them.
We can't leave them like we left Dad!

597
00:40:13.873 --> 00:40:16.710
- That is not what happened!
- It is what happened! It...

598
00:40:18.336 --> 00:40:20.422
[Aneesha] Luke. what's wrong?

599
00:40:22.382 --> 00:40:23.842
Luke.

600
00:40:23.925 --> 00:40:24.926
[Sarah] Luke?

601
00:40:26.845 --> 00:40:28.054
Luke!

602
00:40:30.682 --> 00:40:31.683
More are coming.

603
00:40:32.851 --> 00:40:34.811
[aliens shrieking]

604
00:40:37.939 --> 00:40:42.110
[Clark] We got more! Aliens from the
west! Jesus! Where did they come from?

605
00:40:42.193 --> 00:40:43.588
- [Aneesha] Luke!
- [Clark] Throwers on.

606
00:40:43.612 --> 00:40:45.464
- Circle up! Circle up!
- [Hanley] There's too many!

607
00:40:45.488 --> 00:40:46.573
[Aneesha] Luke.

608
00:40:48.325 --> 00:40:50.702
- Mom!
- Luke!

609
00:40:55.498 --> 00:40:56.708
[Aneesha panting]

610
00:40:57.959 --> 00:41:02.005
Hold on to this. no matter what!
Don't let go! Don't let go!

611
00:41:02.964 --> 00:41:04.132
Mom!

612
00:41:06.927 --> 00:41:09.179
- [breathing heavily]
- [static on radio]

613
00:41:21.441 --> 00:41:23.318
I need you to be right. Nikhil.

614
00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:35.205
[electronic beeping. whirring]

615
00:41:42.796 --> 00:41:44.130
Something's happening.

616
00:41:45.131 --> 00:41:48.176
How much longer you reckon we're
supposed to keep doing this?

617
00:41:50.136 --> 00:41:52.138
How the hell am I
supposed to know?

618
00:41:57.602 --> 00:41:59.997
- [Chrissy] Pull back!
- [Clark] Stay down! You gotta stay down.

619
00:42:00.021 --> 00:42:01.314
[Hanley] Someone got eyes on it?

620
00:42:01.856 --> 00:42:03.536
[Clark] We're not dead
yet. okay? Come on.

621
00:42:04.025 --> 00:42:05.735
[aliens shrieking]

622
00:42:11.324 --> 00:42:12.325
It's happening.

623
00:42:13.410 --> 00:42:15.495
- [people chattering]
- [person 1] What is that?

624
00:42:17.455 --> 00:42:20.584
[person 2] Oh. my
goodness. The size of it.

625
00:42:24.588 --> 00:42:27.007
[operator on comms] Carriers.
do you copy? Do you copy?

626
00:42:27.090 --> 00:42:28.425
[radio chatter]

627
00:42:34.097 --> 00:42:36.474
[operator] We have a target.
I repeat. we have a target.

628
00:42:36.975 --> 00:42:38.101
Fire away.

629
00:43:04.461 --> 00:43:07.714
- [operator 1] Direct hit! Enemy down.
- [radio chatter continues]

630
00:43:10.175 --> 00:43:11.885
[cheering]

631
00:43:13.178 --> 00:43:14.804
[cheering]

632
00:43:16.932 --> 00:43:18.433
[Nikhil] Oh. yeah!

633
00:43:19.017 --> 00:43:20.602
God. I love winning! Huh?

634
00:43:21.394 --> 00:43:22.938
[employees cheering]

635
00:43:23.438 --> 00:43:24.648
[laughs]

636
00:43:24.731 --> 00:43:27.192
Who's giving me a cuddle?
Who's giving me a cuddle?

637
00:43:27.275 --> 00:43:30.362
[analyst] That was the biggest
firework show of all time!

638
00:43:39.621 --> 00:43:41.081
[Jackson] Y'all seeing this?

639
00:43:44.793 --> 00:43:46.127
[aliens shrieking]

640
00:43:46.211 --> 00:43:47.462
[Chrissy] What's happening?

641
00:43:48.588 --> 00:43:49.923
[Jackson] They're dying!

642
00:43:50.757 --> 00:43:52.467
- [Clark] Family's clear!
- [whimpering]

643
00:43:52.551 --> 00:43:54.803
[Clark] Let's go! Let's
go! Everyone. move out!

644
00:43:54.886 --> 00:43:56.429
[cheering. laughing]

645
00:44:00.976 --> 00:44:02.811
[employee] Seven of
their ships are down.

646
00:44:02.894 --> 00:44:06.439
Four in the Pacific. two in
Antarctica. one in Eastern Russia.

647
00:44:08.733 --> 00:44:11.194
Put in a call. Offer aid.

648
00:44:14.906 --> 00:44:15.991
That's right.

649
00:44:17.117 --> 00:44:18.326
Now you see us.

650
00:44:19.119 --> 00:44:21.121
- [cheering. laughing]
- [Maya giggles]

651
00:44:30.589 --> 00:44:31.923
You did it. Mitsuki.

652
00:44:34.134 --> 00:44:36.219
- [both laughing]
- [sheriff] All right. yeah!

653
00:44:51.526 --> 00:44:52.611
[grunts]

654
00:44:55.614 --> 00:44:57.324
- [person] Got ya.
- [Hanley sighs]

655
00:44:57.407 --> 00:45:00.535
There you go. Okay.
Get to that corner.

656
00:45:02.037 --> 00:45:03.038
Hey. there.

657
00:45:03.121 --> 00:45:04.706
[chattering]

658
00:45:05.832 --> 00:45:08.001
- [Hanley] I'll get you some food.
- [Ryder] Hey.

659
00:45:09.127 --> 00:45:10.128
You did good.

660
00:45:11.755 --> 00:45:13.006
[Luke] You too.

661
00:45:14.507 --> 00:45:16.176
[Hanley] Go to the
vehicles. okay?

662
00:45:19.971 --> 00:45:21.306
- [Aneesha sighs]
- Thank you.

663
00:45:21.806 --> 00:45:23.284
- [Hanley] You were good.
- [person] Come on.

664
00:45:23.308 --> 00:45:24.851
[person 2] I got him. I got him.

665
00:45:25.810 --> 00:45:27.562
[Jackson] Hell you
think happened?

666
00:45:27.646 --> 00:45:29.022
[Chrissy] The
aliens just stopped.

667
00:45:29.105 --> 00:45:31.274
[Clark] I don't think we
were the only ones fighting.

668
00:45:36.321 --> 00:45:38.531
Sarah. Sarah.

669
00:45:39.824 --> 00:45:41.117
Sarah. Mommy!

670
00:45:42.827 --> 00:45:44.079
Sarah!

671
00:45:55.423 --> 00:45:56.466
Sarah! [panting]

672
00:45:58.385 --> 00:45:59.469
Sarah!

673
00:46:03.557 --> 00:46:05.934
- Sarah!
- [Clark] Sarah!

674
00:46:06.643 --> 00:46:07.644
Mommy!

675
00:46:10.564 --> 00:46:12.607
- [Clark] Sarah.
- Sarah!

675
00:46:13.305 --> 00:47:13.511
